Coming now to a later period, Marius Victorinus (p. 192, 15 Κ) gives the three accents, tells us that in every word there must be an acute or circumflex, and not more than one, while there may be more than one grave. This is in accord with Greek rules, and thus the theory, success lully launched by Cicero and Varr0, obtained three centuries later. All later grammarians substantially agree-Cf. They all agree, ’ and the conclusion reached above from a studylol Diomedes, that he con- sidered the Latin accentual system as a system based on that 01 the Greeks, but so modified and adapted as to suit the predominating stress accent 01 the Latin language, is applicable to all. See Diomedes p. 431, 1 Κ, and the remarks made thereon.

Having finished the general rules, Pompeius (p. 130, 18 Κ) next gives the principle lor the accentuation 01 compound words: Modo aliquid adicit. Quodsi rorte duae partes orationis sunt, unum accentum habe- bunt, si in unam redigantur. Ut puta male una pars orationis est, sunus una pars orationis est; sed quoniam istae non pro duabus sunt, sed pro una, incipimus dicere malesanus, colligimus utramque, et lam unum ac- centum habebunt. Quotienscumque duae partes orationis in unam col- liguntur, iam quoniam pro una sunt, unum accentum habebunt, prout luerit syllaba illa. Si dicas ‘interea loci,' intereo una pars orationis est, loci una pars orationis est. Quando iarn sic utramque¹ dicis, ut pro una sint, ambae partes unum habebunt accentum. Ergo duae partes orationis quando unam faciunt, necesse est ut unum accentum habeant. The
